WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en
Date: March 25, 2026

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Alex: Alright team, let's dive right into the technical design review for the brand new analytics dashboard we're building. This is the last major feature before we ship version 2.0. David, you've been working on the frontend charting libraries. What have you got for us?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:30.000
David: Hey everyone. So, I took the extensive feedback from last week's session and completely overhauled the charting module. We were originally trying to force Chart.js to work, but the animations felt very clunky when the data changed. We are now exclusively using the Recharts library. The transition animations feel much snappier. I have a prototype running locally right now that I'm screen sharing.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Sarah: Ah, I see it. From a strict engineering standpoint, Recharts is definitely preferred over Chart.js. Because Recharts is built entirely with declarative React components, it plays much nicer with our React DOM tree and reduces bundle size by about 40kb. Great architectural choice, David. But quick question: are the tooltips generated by Recharts accessible to screen readers?

00:00:45.000 --> 00:01:05.000
David: That's the one thing I'm struggling with right now, to be honest. The visual tooltips are perfectly functional when you hover with a mouse, but they aren't fully ARIA compliant yet so keyboard navigation is failing. I need to spend a little more time reading the Recharts documentation to manually force the screen-reader support on those SVG elements.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Alex: We cannot compromise on that. Accessibility is a strict non-negotiable requirement for our upcoming enterprise-tier clients. We promised them section 508 compliance. David, I explicitly need you to ensure all charting tooltips are fully ARIA compliant before we push this new design to the staging branch. Can you reliably have that done by Friday?

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:35.000
David: Yeah, no problem at all. I just need to add the correct focus-states to the nodes. I'll make sure all tooltips are 100% ARIA compliant by Friday. Sarah, before I finalize my props, do we have the actual data schema from the backend locked in yet? I don't want to map fake data.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Sarah: I was literally just looking at the GraphQL resolver for that. Good timing. The data schema for the Sentiment timeline is totally finalized. However, the Action Items aggregate endpoint still needs one more parameter for 'owner' sorting so you can build that specific bar chart you designed. I will update the GraphQL schema for the Action Items endpoint this afternoon so you can pull live data.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Alex: Perfect coordination. So, decision officially made: we are locking in Recharts for the entire platform's analytics suite and deprecating Chart.js. David, finish up the accessibility patching. Sarah, push the GraphQL schema update today. Excellent review session. Let's regroup on Monday morning to see the live data integration working on staging!
